</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="60.[700,1229,193,1419]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
ETYMOLOGY: From the Latin 
<emphasis box="[1078,1146,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">cornu</emphasis>
(horn) and the Latin suffix ­ 
<emphasis box="[955,1003,1191,1214]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">atus</emphasis>
(having the nature of). I refer to the horn like configuration of the parameres.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="60.[700,1229,193,1419]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
REMARKS: The locality label of the 
<typeStatus box="[1178,1228,1278,1301]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">type</typeStatus>
specimen indicates that Atoyac is in ‘‘Estado Veracruz’’; however the only Atoyac locality known to me is located in ‘‘Estado Guerrero’’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
